Unrestrained Central Bankers?
Prague—Recently, one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries has become popular.
The main points of criticism are roughly as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their powers have expanded too quickly, and they are harming the economy.
This argument—strangely, it is popular among ideologically incompatible camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists—is greatly mistaken.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
The level of prices is like a person's body temperature, fluctuating within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
When combating deflation caused by weak demand and curbing high inflation driven by excessive demand, the central bank must be equally "proactive".
Although the battle is entirely symmetric, public perception of it is inexplicably severely biased, especially in countries where people are financially very conservative.
This includes my homeland, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have small savings, and the loan-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs worry about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached a 13-year low last year, and since 2013, when I have served as the deputy governor, the Czech National Bank has been committed to eliminating deflation risks.
Another common complaint about the policies of central banks in developed countries since 2008 is that these policies have caused redistributive effects.
Of course they do, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates pleases savers, while cutting interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong exchange rate; exporters prefer a weak exchange rate.
To be effective, monetary policy must have different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; this is the nature of monetary policy.
Some critics also say that central banks have failed to achieve inflation targets regardless, so their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even place these self-contradictory criticisms in a single sentence, as if they were blaming someone for shooting blanks yet causing casualties.
The reality is that central banks around the world successfully maintained price stability and the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis — and it was an outstanding success, without question.
If it were not for their intervention, their economies would face catastrophic deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a complete collapse of the financial and real sectors.
Obviously, strong action is the right approach to dealing with the crisis (the role of central banks in the outbreak of financial crises is another issue).
In a system that uses a flexible currency without intrinsic value, the quantity of money must change over time in order for the purchasing power of money to remain roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, the central bank has taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; only the eternal mission of status to be achieved.
If you find this assertion arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
The people vote with their wallets.
If their money's purchasing power was severely damaged after 2008, they naturally would seek to exchange their local currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other savings methods).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks have not met their inflation targets.
(Central banks usually define the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%.
) This is certainly unpleasant, but it does not lead to catastrophe, especially considering that falling prices are partly due to supply—rather than demand—shocks, such as a collapse in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil-importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this by increasing sales by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
Probably not.
After all, private companies often experience deviations of 10% or more between planned and actual profits and revenues.
Most businesses have fewer variables in their operating environments than central banks.
If that's the case, how can you expect central banks to always achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I am not saying central banks should not strive to work closely toward their targets.
They absolutely should.
Moreover, they absolutely should not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when judging the central bank, people need to maintain proper restraint.
They indeed need to stop saying untrue things — such as, the central bank's policy arsenal is not only possibly exhausted, but is already near exhaustion.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and an unlimited supply of ammunition to use at will.
These weapons vary in caliber, and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
However, theoretically, the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is unlimited.
Central bank governors should tell critics who are ignorant of the issues at hand to "stop it".
None of our critics have been able to explain clearly and convincingly why price stability is the wrong objective, what key objective the central bank should pursue; and what entirely different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a very simple reason for this: the policies adopted by developed country central banks since the crisis were the correct ones.
In fact, these policies pulled our economies back from the brink.
You're welcome.
